2250
2251// .hash and .gnu.hash sections contain on-disk hash tables that map
2252// symbol names to their dynamic symbol table indices. Their purpose
2253// is to help the dynamic linker resolve symbols quickly. If ELF files
2254// don't have them, the dynamic linker has to do linear search on all
2255// dynamic symbols, which makes programs slower. Therefore, a .hash
2256// section is added to a DSO by default. A .gnu.hash is added if you
2257// give the -hash-style=gnu or -hash-style=both option.
2258//
2259// The Unix semantics of resolving dynamic symbols is somewhat expensive.
2260// Each ELF file has a list of DSOs that the ELF file depends on and a
2261// list of dynamic symbols that need to be resolved from any of the
2262// DSOs. That means resolving all dynamic symbols takes O(m)*O(n)
2263// where m is the number of DSOs and n is the number of dynamic
2264// symbols. For modern large programs, both m and n are large. So
2265// making each step faster by using hash tables substiantially
2266// improves time to load programs.
2267//
2268// (Note that this is not the only way to design the shared library.
2269// For instance, the Windows DLL takes a different approach. On
2270// Windows, each dynamic symbol has a name of DLL from which the symbol
2271// has to be resolved. That makes the cost of symbol resolution O(n).
2272// This disables some hacky techniques you can use on Unix such as
2273// LD_PRELOAD, but this is arguably better semantics than the Unix ones.)
2274//
2275// Due to historical reasons, we have two different hash tables, .hash
2276// and .gnu.hash. They are for the same purpose, and .gnu.hash is a new
2277// and better version of .hash. .hash is just an on-disk hash table, but
2278// .gnu.hash has a bloom filter in addition to a hash table to skip
2279// DSOs very quickly. If you are sure that your dynamic linker knows
2280// about .gnu.hash, you want to specify -hash-style=gnu. Otherwise, a
2281// safe bet is to specify -hash-style=both for backward compatibilty.
2282GnuHashTableSection::GnuHashTableSection()
2283 : SyntheticSection(SHF_ALLOC, SHT_GNU_HASH, Config->Wordsize, ".gnu.hash") {
2284}
2285
2286void GnuHashTableSection::finalizeContents() {
2287 if (OutputSection *Sec = getPartition().DynSymTab->getParent())
2288 getParent()->Link = Sec->SectionIndex;
2289
2290 // Computes bloom filter size in word size. We want to allocate 12
2291 // bits for each symbol. It must be a power of two.
2292 if (Symbols.empty()) {
2293 MaskWords = 1;
2294 } else {
2295 uint64_t NumBits = Symbols.size() * 12;
2296 MaskWords = NextPowerOf2(NumBits / (Config->Wordsize * 8));
2297 }
2298
2299 Size = 16; // Header
2300 Size += Config->Wordsize * MaskWords; // Bloom filter
2301 Size += NBuckets * 4; // Hash buckets
2302 Size += Symbols.size() * 4; // Hash values
2303}
2304
2305void GnuHashTableSection::writeTo(uint8_t *Buf) {
2306 // The output buffer is not guaranteed to be zero-cleared because we pre-
2307 // fill executable sections with trap instructions. This is a precaution
2308 // for that case, which happens only when -no-rosegment is given.
2309 memset(Buf, 0, Size);
2310
2311 // Write a header.
2312 write32(Buf, NBuckets);
2313 write32(Buf + 4, getPartition().DynSymTab->getNumSymbols() - Symbols.size());
2314 write32(Buf + 8, MaskWords);
2315 write32(Buf + 12, Shift2);
2316 Buf += 16;
2317
2318 // Write a bloom filter and a hash table.
2319 writeBloomFilter(Buf);
2320 Buf += Config->Wordsize * MaskWords;
2321 writeHashTable(Buf);
2322}
2323
2324// This function writes a 2-bit bloom filter. This bloom filter alone
2325// usually filters out 80% or more of all symbol lookups [1].
2326// The dynamic linker uses the hash table only when a symbol is not
2327// filtered out by a bloom filter.
2328//
2329// [1] Ulrich Drepper (2011), "How To Write Shared Libraries" (Ver. 4.1.2),
2330// p.9, https://www.akkadia.org/drepper/dsohowto.pdf
2331void GnuHashTableSection::writeBloomFilter(uint8_t *Buf) {
2332 unsigned C = Config->Is64 ? 64 : 32;
2333 for (const Entry &Sym : Symbols) {
2334 // When C = 64, we choose a word with bits [6:...] and set 1 to two bits in
2335 // the word using bits [0:5] and [26:31].
2336 size_t I = (Sym.Hash / C) & (MaskWords - 1);
2337 uint64_t Val = readUint(Buf + I * Config->Wordsize);
2338 Val |= uint64_t(1) << (Sym.Hash % C);
2339 Val |= uint64_t(1) << ((Sym.Hash >> Shift2) % C);
2340 writeUint(Buf + I * Config->Wordsize, Val);
2341 }
2342}
2343
2344void GnuHashTableSection::writeHashTable(uint8_t *Buf) {
2345 uint32_t *Buckets = reinterpret_cast<uint32_t *>(Buf);
2346 uint32_t OldBucket = -1;
2347 uint32_t *Values = Buckets + NBuckets;
2348 for (auto I = Symbols.begin(), E = Symbols.end(); I != E; ++I) {
2349 // Write a hash value. It represents a sequence of chains that share the
2350 // same hash modulo value. The last element of each chain is terminated by
2351 // LSB 1.
2352 uint32_t Hash = I->Hash;
2353 bool IsLastInChain = (I + 1) == E || I->BucketIdx != (I + 1)->BucketIdx;
2354 Hash = IsLastInChain ? Hash | 1 : Hash & ~1;
2355 write32(Values++, Hash);
2356
2357 if (I->BucketIdx == OldBucket)
2358 continue;
2359 // Write a hash bucket. Hash buckets contain indices in the following hash
2360 // value table.
2361 write32(Buckets + I->BucketIdx,
2362 getPartition().DynSymTab->getSymbolIndex(I->Sym));
2363 OldBucket = I->BucketIdx;
2364 }
2365}
2366
2367static uint32_t hashGnu(StringRef Name) {
2368 uint32_t H = 5381;
2369 for (uint8_t C : Name)
2370 H = (H << 5) + H + C;
2371 return H;
2372}
2373
2374// Add symbols to this symbol hash table. Note that this function
2375// destructively sort a given vector -- which is needed because
2376// GNU-style hash table places some sorting requirements.
2377void GnuHashTableSection::addSymbols(std::vector<SymbolTableEntry> &V) {
2378 // We cannot use 'auto' for Mid because GCC 6.1 cannot deduce
2379 // its type correctly.
2380 std::vector<SymbolTableEntry>::iterator Mid =
2381 std::stable_partition(V.begin(), V.end(), [&](const SymbolTableEntry &S) {
2382 return !S.Sym->isDefined() || S.Sym->Partition != Partition;
2383 });
2384
2385 // We chose load factor 4 for the on-disk hash table. For each hash
2386 // collision, the dynamic linker will compare a uint32_t hash value.
2387 // Since the integer comparison is quite fast, we believe we can
2388 // make the load factor even larger. 4 is just a conservative choice.
2389 //
2390 // Note that we don't want to create a zero-sized hash table because
2391 // Android loader as of 2018 doesn't like a .gnu.hash containing such
2392 // table. If that's the case, we create a hash table with one unused
2393 // dummy slot.
2394 NBuckets = std::max<size_t>((V.end() - Mid) / 4, 1);
2395
2396 if (Mid == V.end())
2397 return;
2398
2399 for (SymbolTableEntry &Ent : llvm::make_range(Mid, V.end())) {
2400 Symbol *B = Ent.Sym;
2401 uint32_t Hash = hashGnu(B->getName());
2402 uint32_t BucketIdx = Hash % NBuckets;
2403 Symbols.push_back({B, Ent.StrTabOffset, Hash, BucketIdx});
2404 }
2405
2406 llvm::stable_sort(Symbols, [](const Entry &L, const Entry &R) {
2407 return L.BucketIdx < R.BucketIdx;
2408 });
2409
2410 V.erase(Mid, V.end());
2411 for (const Entry &Ent : Symbols)
2412 V.push_back({Ent.Sym, Ent.StrTabOffset});
2413}
2414
2415HashTableSection::HashTableSection()
2416 : SyntheticSection(SHF_ALLOC, SHT_HASH, 4, ".hash") {
2417 this->Entsize = 4;
2418}
2419
2420void HashTableSection::finalizeContents() {
2421 SymbolTableBaseSection *SymTab = getPartition().DynSymTab;
2422
2423 if (OutputSection *Sec = SymTab->getParent())
2424 getParent()->Link = Sec->SectionIndex;
2425
2426 unsigned NumEntries = 2; // nbucket and nchain.
2427 NumEntries += SymTab->getNumSymbols(); // The chain entries.
2428
2429 // Create as many buckets as there are symbols.
2430 NumEntries += SymTab->getNumSymbols();
2431 this->Size = NumEntries * 4;
2432}
2433
2434void HashTableSection::writeTo(uint8_t *Buf) {
2435 SymbolTableBaseSection *SymTab = getPartition().DynSymTab;
2436
2437 // See comment in GnuHashTableSection::writeTo.
2438 memset(Buf, 0, Size);
2439
2440 unsigned NumSymbols = SymTab->getNumSymbols();
2441
2442 uint32_t *P = reinterpret_cast<uint32_t *>(Buf);
2443 write32(P++, NumSymbols); // nbucket
2444 write32(P++, NumSymbols); // nchain
2445
2446 uint32_t *Buckets = P;
2447 uint32_t *Chains = P + NumSymbols;
2448
2449 for (const SymbolTableEntry &S : SymTab->getSymbols()) {
2450 Symbol *Sym = S.Sym;
2451 StringRef Name = Sym->getName();
2452 unsigned I = Sym->DynsymIndex;
2453 uint32_t Hash = hashSysV(Name) % NumSymbols;
2454 Chains[I] = Buckets[Hash];
2455 write32(Buckets + Hash, I);
2456 }
2457}

2459// On PowerPC64 the lazy symbol resolvers go into the `global linkage table`
2460// in the .glink section, rather then the typical .plt section.
2461PltSection::PltSection(bool IsIplt)
2462 : SyntheticSection(
2463 SHF_ALLOC | SHF_EXECINSTR, SHT_PROGBITS, 16,
2464 (Config->EMachine == EM_PPC || Config->EMachine == EM_PPC64)
2465 ? ".glink"
2466 : ".plt"),
2467 HeaderSize(!IsIplt || Config->ZRetpolineplt ? Target->PltHeaderSize : 0),
2468 IsIplt(IsIplt) {
2469 // The PLT needs to be writable on SPARC as the dynamic linker will
2470 // modify the instructions in the PLT entries.
2471 if (Config->EMachine == EM_SPARCV9)
2472 this->Flags |= SHF_WRITE;
2473}
2474
2475void PltSection::writeTo(uint8_t *Buf) {
2476 if (Config->EMachine == EM_PPC) {
2477 writePPC32GlinkSection(Buf, Entries.size());
2478 return;
2479 }
2480
2481 // At beginning of PLT or retpoline IPLT, we have code to call the dynamic
2482 // linker to resolve dynsyms at runtime. Write such code.
2483 if (HeaderSize)
2484 Target->writePltHeader(Buf);
2485 size_t Off = HeaderSize;
2486
2487 RelocationBaseSection *RelSec = IsIplt ? In.RelaIplt : In.RelaPlt;
2488
2489 // The IPlt is immediately after the Plt, account for this in RelOff
2490 size_t PltOff = IsIplt ? In.Plt->getSize() : 0;
2491
2492 for (size_t I = 0, E = Entries.size(); I != E; ++I) {
2493 const Symbol *B = Entries[I];
2494 unsigned RelOff = RelSec->Entsize * I + PltOff;
2495 uint64_t Got = B->getGotPltVA();
2496 uint64_t Plt = this->getVA() + Off;
2497 Target->writePlt(Buf + Off, Got, Plt, B->PltIndex, RelOff);
2498 Off += Target->PltEntrySize;
2499 }
2500}

2525// The string hash function for .gdb_index.
2526static uint32_t computeGdbHash(StringRef S) {
2527 uint32_t H = 0;
2528 for (uint8_t C : S)
2529 H = H * 67 + toLower(C) - 113;
2530 return H;
2531}

2533GdbIndexSection::GdbIndexSection()
2534 : SyntheticSection(0, SHT_PROGBITS, 1, ".gdb_index") {}

2536// Returns the desired size of an on-disk hash table for a .gdb_index section.
2537// There's a tradeoff between size and collision rate. We aim 75% utilization.
2538size_t GdbIndexSection::computeSymtabSize() const {
2539 return std::max<size_t>(NextPowerOf2(Symbols.size() * 4 / 3), 1024);
2540}
2541
2542// Compute the output section size.
2543void GdbIndexSection::initOutputSize() {
2544 Size = sizeof(GdbIndexHeader) + computeSymtabSize() * 8;
2545
2546 for (GdbChunk &Chunk : Chunks)
2547 Size += Chunk.CompilationUnits.size() * 16 + Chunk.AddressAreas.size() * 20;
2548
2549 // Add the constant pool size if exists.
2550 if (!Symbols.empty()) {
2551 GdbSymbol &Sym = Symbols.back();
2552 Size += Sym.NameOff + Sym.Name.size() + 1;
2553 }
2554}

2556static std::vector<InputSection *> getDebugInfoSections() {
2557 std::vector<InputSection *> Ret;
2558 for (InputSectionBase *S : InputSections)
2559 if (InputSection *IS = dyn_cast<InputSection>(S))
2560 if (IS->Name == ".debug_info")
2561 Ret.push_back(IS);
2562 return Ret;
2563}

2565static std::vector<GdbIndexSection::CuEntry> readCuList(DWARFContext &Dwarf) {
2566 std::vector<GdbIndexSection::CuEntry> Ret;
2567 for (std::unique_ptr<DWARFUnit> &Cu : Dwarf.compile_units())
2568 Ret.push_back({Cu->getOffset(), Cu->getLength() + 4});
2569 return Ret;
2570}
2571
2572static std::vector<GdbIndexSection::AddressEntry>
2573readAddressAreas(DWARFContext &Dwarf, InputSection *Sec) {
2574 std::vector<GdbIndexSection::AddressEntry> Ret;
2575
2576 uint32_t CuIdx = 0;
2577 for (std::unique_ptr<DWARFUnit> &Cu : Dwarf.compile_units()) {
2578 Expected<DWARFAddressRangesVector> Ranges = Cu->collectAddressRanges();
2579 if (!Ranges) {
2580 error(toString(Sec) + ": " + toString(Ranges.takeError()));
2581 return {};
2582 }
2583
2584 ArrayRef<InputSectionBase *> Sections = Sec->File->getSections();
2585 for (DWARFAddressRange &R : *Ranges) {
2586 if (R.SectionIndex == -1ULL)
2587 continue;
2588 InputSectionBase *S = Sections[R.SectionIndex];
2589 if (!S || S == &InputSection::Discarded || !S->isLive())
2590 continue;
2591 // Range list with zero size has no effect.
2592 if (R.LowPC == R.HighPC)
2593 continue;
2594 auto *IS = cast<InputSection>(S);
2595 uint64_t Offset = IS->getOffsetInFile();
2596 Ret.push_back({IS, R.LowPC - Offset, R.HighPC - Offset, CuIdx});
2597 }
2598 ++CuIdx;
2599 }
2600
2601 return Ret;
2602}
2603
2604template <class ELFT>
2605static std::vector<GdbIndexSection::NameAttrEntry>
2606readPubNamesAndTypes(const LLDDwarfObj<ELFT> &Obj,
2607 const std::vector<GdbIndexSection::CuEntry> &CUs) {
2608 const DWARFSection &PubNames = Obj.getGnuPubNamesSection();
2609 const DWARFSection &PubTypes = Obj.getGnuPubTypesSection();
2610
2611 std::vector<GdbIndexSection::NameAttrEntry> Ret;
2612 for (const DWARFSection *Pub : {&PubNames, &PubTypes}) {
2613 DWARFDebugPubTable Table(Obj, *Pub, Config->IsLE, true);
2614 for (const DWARFDebugPubTable::Set &Set : Table.getData()) {
2615 // The value written into the constant pool is Kind << 24 | CuIndex. As we
2616 // don't know how many compilation units precede this object to compute
2617 // CuIndex, we compute (Kind << 24 | CuIndexInThisObject) instead, and add
2618 // the number of preceding compilation units later.
2619 uint32_t I =
2620 lower_bound(CUs, Set.Offset,
2621 [](GdbIndexSection::CuEntry CU, uint32_t Offset) {
2622 return CU.CuOffset < Offset;
2623 }) -
2624 CUs.begin();
2625 for (const DWARFDebugPubTable::Entry &Ent : Set.Entries)
2626 Ret.push_back({{Ent.Name, computeGdbHash(Ent.Name)},
2627 (Ent.Descriptor.toBits() << 24) | I});
2628 }
2629 }
2630 return Ret;
2631}
2632
2633// Create a list of symbols from a given list of symbol names and types
2634// by uniquifying them by name.
2635static std::vector<GdbIndexSection::GdbSymbol>
2636createSymbols(ArrayRef<std::vector<GdbIndexSection::NameAttrEntry>> NameAttrs,
2637 const std::vector<GdbIndexSection::GdbChunk> &Chunks) {
2638 using GdbSymbol = GdbIndexSection::GdbSymbol;
2639 using NameAttrEntry = GdbIndexSection::NameAttrEntry;
2640
2641 // For each chunk, compute the number of compilation units preceding it.
2642 uint32_t CuIdx = 0;
2643 std::vector<uint32_t> CuIdxs(Chunks.size());
2644 for (uint32_t I = 0, E = Chunks.size(); I != E; ++I) {
2645 CuIdxs[I] = CuIdx;
2646 CuIdx += Chunks[I].CompilationUnits.size();
2647 }
2648
2649 // The number of symbols we will handle in this function is of the order
2650 // of millions for very large executables, so we use multi-threading to
2651 // speed it up.
2652 size_t NumShards = 32;
2653 size_t Concurrency = 1;
2654 if (ThreadsEnabled)
2655 Concurrency =
2656 std::min<size_t>(PowerOf2Floor(hardware_concurrency()), NumShards);
2657
2658 // A sharded map to uniquify symbols by name.
2659 std::vector<DenseMap<CachedHashStringRef, size_t>> Map(NumShards);
2660 size_t Shift = 32 - countTrailingZeros(NumShards);
2661
2662 // Instantiate GdbSymbols while uniqufying them by name.
2663 std::vector<std::vector<GdbSymbol>> Symbols(NumShards);
2664 parallelForEachN(0, Concurrency, [&](size_t ThreadId) {
2665 uint32_t I = 0;
2666 for (ArrayRef<NameAttrEntry> Entries : NameAttrs) {
2667 for (const NameAttrEntry &Ent : Entries) {
2668 size_t ShardId = Ent.Name.hash() >> Shift;
2669 if ((ShardId & (Concurrency - 1)) != ThreadId)
2670 continue;
2671
2672 uint32_t V = Ent.CuIndexAndAttrs + CuIdxs[I];
2673 size_t &Idx = Map[ShardId][Ent.Name];
2674 if (Idx) {
2675 Symbols[ShardId][Idx - 1].CuVector.push_back(V);
2676 continue;
2677 }
2678
2679 Idx = Symbols[ShardId].size() + 1;
2680 Symbols[ShardId].push_back({Ent.Name, {V}, 0, 0});
2681 }
2682 ++I;
2683 }
2684 });
2685
2686 size_t NumSymbols = 0;
2687 for (ArrayRef<GdbSymbol> V : Symbols)
2688 NumSymbols += V.size();
2689
2690 // The return type is a flattened vector, so we'll copy each vector
2691 // contents to Ret.
2692 std::vector<GdbSymbol> Ret;
2693 Ret.reserve(NumSymbols);
2694 for (std::vector<GdbSymbol> &Vec : Symbols)
2695 for (GdbSymbol &Sym : Vec)
2696 Ret.push_back(std::move(Sym));
2697
2698 // CU vectors and symbol names are adjacent in the output file.
2699 // We can compute their offsets in the output file now.
2700 size_t Off = 0;
2701 for (GdbSymbol &Sym : Ret) {
2702 Sym.CuVectorOff = Off;
2703 Off += (Sym.CuVector.size() + 1) * 4;
2704 }
2705 for (GdbSymbol &Sym : Ret) {
2706 Sym.NameOff = Off;
2707 Off += Sym.Name.size() + 1;
2708 }
2709
2710 return Ret;
2711}
2712
2713// Returns a newly-created .gdb_index section.
2714template <class ELFT> GdbIndexSection *GdbIndexSection::create() {
2715 std::vector<InputSection *> Sections = getDebugInfoSections();
2716
2717 // .debug_gnu_pub{names,types} are useless in executables.
2718 // They are present in input object files solely for creating
2719 // a .gdb_index. So we can remove them from the output.
2720 for (InputSectionBase *S : InputSections)
2721 if (S->Name == ".debug_gnu_pubnames" || S->Name == ".debug_gnu_pubtypes")
2722 S->markDead();
2723
2724 std::vector<GdbChunk> Chunks(Sections.size());
2725 std::vector<std::vector<NameAttrEntry>> NameAttrs(Sections.size());
2726
2727 parallelForEachN(0, Sections.size(), [&](size_t I) {
2728 ObjFile<ELFT> *File = Sections[I]->getFile<ELFT>();
2729 DWARFContext Dwarf(make_unique<LLDDwarfObj<ELFT>>(File));
2730
2731 Chunks[I].Sec = Sections[I];
2732 Chunks[I].CompilationUnits = readCuList(Dwarf);
2733 Chunks[I].AddressAreas = readAddressAreas(Dwarf, Sections[I]);
2734 NameAttrs[I] = readPubNamesAndTypes<ELFT>(
2735 static_cast<const LLDDwarfObj<ELFT> &>(Dwarf.getDWARFObj()),
2736 Chunks[I].CompilationUnits);
2737 });
2738
2739 auto *Ret = make<GdbIndexSection>();
2740 Ret->Chunks = std::move(Chunks);
2741 Ret->Symbols = createSymbols(NameAttrs, Ret->Chunks);
2742 Ret->initOutputSize();
2743 return Ret;
2744}
2745
2746void GdbIndexSection::writeTo(uint8_t *Buf) {
2747 // Write the header.
2748 auto *Hdr = reinterpret_cast<GdbIndexHeader *>(Buf);
2749 uint8_t *Start = Buf;
2750 Hdr->Version = 7;
2751 Buf += sizeof(*Hdr);
2752
2753 // Write the CU list.
2754 Hdr->CuListOff = Buf - Start;
2755 for (GdbChunk &Chunk : Chunks) {
2756 for (CuEntry &Cu : Chunk.CompilationUnits) {
2757 write64le(Buf, Chunk.Sec->OutSecOff + Cu.CuOffset);
2758 write64le(Buf + 8, Cu.CuLength);
2759 Buf += 16;
2760 }
2761 }
2762
2763 // Write the address area.
2764 Hdr->CuTypesOff = Buf - Start;
2765 Hdr->AddressAreaOff = Buf - Start;
2766 uint32_t CuOff = 0;
2767 for (GdbChunk &Chunk : Chunks) {
2768 for (AddressEntry &E : Chunk.AddressAreas) {
2769 uint64_t BaseAddr = E.Section->getVA(0);
2770 write64le(Buf, BaseAddr + E.LowAddress);
2771 write64le(Buf + 8, BaseAddr + E.HighAddress);
2772 write32le(Buf + 16, E.CuIndex + CuOff);
2773 Buf += 20;
2774 }
2775 CuOff += Chunk.CompilationUnits.size();
2776 }
2777
2778 // Write the on-disk open-addressing hash table containing symbols.
2779 Hdr->SymtabOff = Buf - Start;
2780 size_t SymtabSize = computeSymtabSize();
2781 uint32_t Mask = SymtabSize - 1;
2782
2783 for (GdbSymbol &Sym : Symbols) {
2784 uint32_t H = Sym.Name.hash();
2785 uint32_t I = H & Mask;
2786 uint32_t Step = ((H * 17) & Mask) | 1;
2787
2788 while (read32le(Buf + I * 8))
2789 I = (I + Step) & Mask;
2790
2791 write32le(Buf + I * 8, Sym.NameOff);
2792 write32le(Buf + I * 8 + 4, Sym.CuVectorOff);
2793 }
2794
2795 Buf += SymtabSize * 8;
2796
2797 // Write the string pool.
2798 Hdr->ConstantPoolOff = Buf - Start;
2799 parallelForEach(Symbols, [&](GdbSymbol &Sym) {
2800 memcpy(Buf + Sym.NameOff, Sym.Name.data(), Sym.Name.size());
2801 });
2802
2803 // Write the CU vectors.
2804 for (GdbSymbol &Sym : Symbols) {
2805 write32le(Buf, Sym.CuVector.size());
2806 Buf += 4;
2807 for (uint32_t Val : Sym.CuVector) {
2808 write32le(Buf, Val);
2809 Buf += 4;
2810 }
2811 }
2812}
2813
2814bool GdbIndexSection::isNeeded() const { return !Chunks.empty(); }

2816EhFrameHeader::EhFrameHeader()
2817 : SyntheticSection(SHF_ALLOC, SHT_PROGBITS, 4, ".eh_frame_hdr") {}
2818
2819void EhFrameHeader::writeTo(uint8_t *Buf) {
2820 // Unlike most sections, the EhFrameHeader section is written while writing
2821 // another section, namely EhFrameSection, which calls the write() function
2822 // below from its writeTo() function. This is necessary because the contents
2823 // of EhFrameHeader depend on the relocated contents of EhFrameSection and we
2824 // don't know which order the sections will be written in.
2825}
2826
2827// .eh_frame_hdr contains a binary search table of pointers to FDEs.
2828// Each entry of the search table consists of two values,
2829// the starting PC from where FDEs covers, and the FDE's address.
2830// It is sorted by PC.
2831void EhFrameHeader::write() {
2832 uint8_t *Buf = Out::BufferStart + getParent()->Offset + OutSecOff;
2833 using FdeData = EhFrameSection::FdeData;
2834
2835 std::vector<FdeData> Fdes = getPartition().EhFrame->getFdeData();
2836
2837 Buf[0] = 1;
2838 Buf[1] = DW_EH_PE_pcrel | DW_EH_PE_sdata4;
2839 Buf[2] = DW_EH_PE_udata4;
2840 Buf[3] = DW_EH_PE_datarel | DW_EH_PE_sdata4;
2841 write32(Buf + 4,
2842 getPartition().EhFrame->getParent()->Addr - this->getVA() - 4);
2843 write32(Buf + 8, Fdes.size());
2844 Buf += 12;
2845
2846 for (FdeData &Fde : Fdes) {
2847 write32(Buf, Fde.PcRel);
2848 write32(Buf + 4, Fde.FdeVARel);
2849 Buf += 8;
2850 }
2851}
2852
2853size_t EhFrameHeader::getSize() const {
2854 // .eh_frame_hdr has a 12 bytes header followed by an array of FDEs.
2855 return 12 + getPartition().EhFrame->NumFdes * 8;
2856}
2857
2858bool EhFrameHeader::isNeeded() const {
2859 return isLive() && getPartition().EhFrame->isNeeded();
2860}

2887
2888void VersionDefinitionSection::writeOne(uint8_t *Buf, uint32_t Index,
2889 StringRef Name, size_t NameOff) {
2890 uint16_t Flags = Index == 1 ? VER_FLG_BASE : 0;
2891
2892 // Write a verdef.
2893 write16(Buf, 1); // vd_version
2894 write16(Buf + 2, Flags); // vd_flags
2895 write16(Buf + 4, Index); // vd_ndx
2896 write16(Buf + 6, 1); // vd_cnt
2897 write32(Buf + 8, hashSysV(Name)); // vd_hash
2898 write32(Buf + 12, 20); // vd_aux
2899 write32(Buf + 16, 28); // vd_next
2900
2901 // Write a veraux.
2902 write32(Buf + 20, NameOff); // vda_name
2903 write32(Buf + 24, 0); // vda_next
2904}

2916 write32(Buf + 16, 0); // vd_next
2917}

2952void elf::addVerneed(Symbol *SS) {
2953 auto &File = cast<SharedFile>(*SS->File);
2954 if (SS->VerdefIndex == VER_NDX_GLOBAL) {
2955 SS->VersionId = VER_NDX_GLOBAL;
2956 return;
2957 }
2958
2959 if (File.Vernauxs.empty())
2960 File.Vernauxs.resize(File.Verdefs.size());
2961

2963 // already allocated one. The verdef identifiers cover the range
2964 // [1..getVerDefNum()]; this causes the vernaux identifiers to start from
2965 // getVerDefNum()+1.
2966 if (File.Vernauxs[SS->VerdefIndex] == 0)
2967 File.Vernauxs[SS->VerdefIndex] = ++SharedFile::VernauxNum + getVerDefNum();

2969 SS->VersionId = File.Vernauxs[SS->VerdefIndex];

3053
3054void MergeTailSection::finalizeContents() {
3055 // Add all string pieces to the string table builder to create section
3056 // contents.
3057 for (MergeInputSection *Sec : Sections)
3058 for (size_t I = 0, E = Sec->Pieces.size(); I != E; ++I)
3059 if (Sec->Pieces[I].Live)
3060 Builder.add(Sec->getData(I));
3061
3062 // Fix the string table content. After this, the contents will never change.
3063 Builder.finalize();
3064
3065 // finalize() fixed tail-optimized strings, so we can now get
3066 // offsets of strings. Get an offset for each string and save it
3067 // to a corresponding StringPiece for easy access.
3068 for (MergeInputSection *Sec : Sections)
3069 for (size_t I = 0, E = Sec->Pieces.size(); I != E; ++I)
3070 if (Sec->Pieces[I].Live)
3071 Sec->Pieces[I].OutputOff = Builder.getOffset(Sec->getData(I));
3072}

3074void MergeNoTailSection::writeTo(uint8_t *Buf) {
3075 for (size_t I = 0; I < NumShards; ++I)
3076 Shards[I].write(Buf + ShardOffsets[I]);
3077}
3078
3079// This function is very hot (i.e. it can take several seconds to finish)
3080// because sometimes the number of inputs is in an order of magnitude of
3081// millions. So, we use multi-threading.
3082//
3083// For any strings S and T, we know S is not mergeable with T if S's hash
3084// value is different from T's. If that's the case, we can safely put S and
3085// T into different string builders without worrying about merge misses.
3086// We do it in parallel.
3087void MergeNoTailSection::finalizeContents() {
3088 // Initializes string table builders.
3089 for (size_t I = 0; I < NumShards; ++I)
3090 Shards.emplace_back(StringTableBuilder::RAW, Alignment);
3091
3092 // Concurrency level. Must be a power of 2 to avoid expensive modulo
3093 // operations in the following tight loop.
3094 size_t Concurrency = 1;
3095 if (ThreadsEnabled)
3096 Concurrency =
3097 std::min<size_t>(PowerOf2Floor(hardware_concurrency()), NumShards);
3098
3099 // Add section pieces to the builders.
3100 parallelForEachN(0, Concurrency, [&](size_t ThreadId) {
3101 for (MergeInputSection *Sec : Sections) {
3102 for (size_t I = 0, E = Sec->Pieces.size(); I != E; ++I) {
3103 if (!Sec->Pieces[I].Live)
3104 continue;
3105 size_t ShardId = getShardId(Sec->Pieces[I].Hash);
3106 if ((ShardId & (Concurrency - 1)) == ThreadId)
3107 Sec->Pieces[I].OutputOff = Shards[ShardId].add(Sec->getData(I));
3108 }
3109 }
3110 });
3111
3112 // Compute an in-section offset for each shard.
3113 size_t Off = 0;
3114 for (size_t I = 0; I < NumShards; ++I) {
3115 Shards[I].finalizeInOrder();
3116 if (Shards[I].getSize() > 0)
3117 Off = alignTo(Off, Alignment);
3118 ShardOffsets[I] = Off;
3119 Off += Shards[I].getSize();
3120 }
3121 Size = Off;
3122
3123 // So far, section pieces have offsets from beginning of shards, but
3124 // we want offsets from beginning of the whole section. Fix them.
3125 parallelForEach(Sections, [&](MergeInputSection *Sec) {
3126 for (size_t I = 0, E = Sec->Pieces.size(); I != E; ++I)
3127 if (Sec->Pieces[I].Live)
3128 Sec->Pieces[I].OutputOff +=
3129 ShardOffsets[getShardId(Sec->Pieces[I].Hash)];
3130 });
3131}

3133static MergeSyntheticSection *createMergeSynthetic(StringRef Name,
3134 uint32_t Type,
3135 uint64_t Flags,
3136 uint32_t Alignment) {
3137 bool ShouldTailMerge = (Flags & SHF_STRINGS) && Config->Optimize >= 2;
3138 if (ShouldTailMerge)
3139 return make<MergeTailSection>(Name, Type, Flags, Alignment);
3140 return make<MergeNoTailSection>(Name, Type, Flags, Alignment);
3141}

3143template <class ELFT> void elf::splitSections() {
3144 // splitIntoPieces needs to be called on each MergeInputSection
3145 // before calling finalizeContents().
3146 parallelForEach(InputSections, [](InputSectionBase *Sec) {
3147 if (auto *S = dyn_cast<MergeInputSection>(Sec))
3148 S->splitIntoPieces();
3149 else if (auto *Eh = dyn_cast<EhInputSection>(Sec))
3150 Eh->split<ELFT>();
3151 });
3152}
3153
3154// This function scans over the inputsections to create mergeable
3155// synthetic sections.
3156//
3157// It removes MergeInputSections from the input section array and adds
3158// new synthetic sections at the location of the first input section
3159// that it replaces. It then finalizes each synthetic section in order
3160// to compute an output offset for each piece of each input section.
3161void elf::mergeSections() {
3162 std::vector<MergeSyntheticSection *> MergeSections;
3163 for (InputSectionBase *&S : InputSections) {
3164 MergeInputSection *MS = dyn_cast<MergeInputSection>(S);
3165 if (!MS)
3166 continue;
3167
3168 // We do not want to handle sections that are not alive, so just remove
3169 // them instead of trying to merge.
3170 if (!MS->isLive()) {
3171 S = nullptr;
3172 continue;
3173 }
3174
3175 StringRef OutsecName = getOutputSectionName(MS);
3176
3177 auto I = llvm::find_if(MergeSections, [=](MergeSyntheticSection *Sec) {
3178 // While we could create a single synthetic section for two different
3179 // values of Entsize, it is better to take Entsize into consideration.
3180 //
3181 // With a single synthetic section no two pieces with different Entsize
3182 // could be equal, so we may as well have two sections.
3183 //
3184 // Using Entsize in here also allows us to propagate it to the synthetic
3185 // section.
3186 return Sec->Name == OutsecName && Sec->Flags == MS->Flags &&
3187 Sec->Entsize == MS->Entsize && Sec->Alignment == MS->Alignment;
3188 });
3189 if (I == MergeSections.end()) {
3190 MergeSyntheticSection *Syn =
3191 createMergeSynthetic(OutsecName, MS->Type, MS->Flags, MS->Alignment);
3192 MergeSections.push_back(Syn);
3193 I = std::prev(MergeSections.end());
3194 S = Syn;
3195 Syn->Entsize = MS->Entsize;
3196 } else {
3197 S = nullptr;
3198 }
3199 (*I)->addSection(MS);
3200 }
3201 for (auto *MS : MergeSections)
3202 MS->finalizeContents();
3203
3204 std::vector<InputSectionBase *> &V = InputSections;
3205 V.erase(std::remove(V.begin(), V.end(), nullptr), V.end());
3206}

3250// References to .ARM.Extab Sections have bit 31 clear and are not the
3251// special EXIDX_CANTUNWIND bit-pattern.
3252static bool isExtabRef(uint32_t Unwind) {
3253 return (Unwind & 0x80000000) == 0 && Unwind != 0x1;
3254}
3255
3256// Return true if the .ARM.exidx section Cur can be merged into the .ARM.exidx
3257// section Prev, where Cur follows Prev in the table. This can be done if the
3258// unwinding instructions in Cur are identical to Prev. Linker generated
3259// EXIDX_CANTUNWIND entries are represented by nullptr as they do not have an
3260// InputSection.
3261static bool isDuplicateArmExidxSec(InputSection *Prev, InputSection *Cur) {
3262
3263 struct ExidxEntry {
3264 ulittle32_t Fn;
3265 ulittle32_t Unwind;
3266 };
3267 // Get the last table Entry from the previous .ARM.exidx section. If Prev is
3268 // nullptr then it will be a synthesized EXIDX_CANTUNWIND entry.
3269 ExidxEntry PrevEntry = {ulittle32_t(0), ulittle32_t(1)};
3270 if (Prev)
3271 PrevEntry = Prev->getDataAs<ExidxEntry>().back();
3272 if (isExtabRef(PrevEntry.Unwind))
3273 return false;
3274
3275 // We consider the unwind instructions of an .ARM.exidx table entry
3276 // a duplicate if the previous unwind instructions if:
3277 // - Both are the special EXIDX_CANTUNWIND.
3278 // - Both are the same inline unwind instructions.
3279 // We do not attempt to follow and check links into .ARM.extab tables as
3280 // consecutive identical entries are rare and the effort to check that they
3281 // are identical is high.
3282
3283 // If Cur is nullptr then this is synthesized EXIDX_CANTUNWIND entry.
3284 if (Cur == nullptr)
3285 return PrevEntry.Unwind == 1;
3286
3287 for (const ExidxEntry Entry : Cur->getDataAs<ExidxEntry>())
3288 if (isExtabRef(Entry.Unwind) || Entry.Unwind != PrevEntry.Unwind)
3289 return false;
3290
3291 // All table entries in this .ARM.exidx Section can be merged into the
3292 // previous Section.
3293 return true;
3294}
3295
3296// The .ARM.exidx table must be sorted in ascending order of the address of the
3297// functions the table describes. Optionally duplicate adjacent table entries
3298// can be removed. At the end of the function the ExecutableSections must be
3299// sorted in ascending order of address, Sentinel is set to the InputSection
3300// with the highest address and any InputSections that have mergeable
3301// .ARM.exidx table entries are removed from it.
3302void ARMExidxSyntheticSection::finalizeContents() {
3303 // Sort the executable sections that may or may not have associated
3304 // .ARM.exidx sections by order of ascending address. This requires the
3305 // relative positions of InputSections to be known.
3306 auto CompareByFilePosition = [](const InputSection *A,
3307 const InputSection *B) {
3308 OutputSection *AOut = A->getParent();
3309 OutputSection *BOut = B->getParent();
3310
3311 if (AOut != BOut)
3312 return AOut->SectionIndex < BOut->SectionIndex;
3313 return A->OutSecOff < B->OutSecOff;
3314 };
3315 llvm::stable_sort(ExecutableSections, CompareByFilePosition);
3316 Sentinel = ExecutableSections.back();
3317 // Optionally merge adjacent duplicate entries.
3318 if (Config->MergeArmExidx) {
3319 std::vector<InputSection *> SelectedSections;
3320 SelectedSections.reserve(ExecutableSections.size());
3321 SelectedSections.push_back(ExecutableSections[0]);
3322 size_t Prev = 0;
3323 for (size_t I = 1; I < ExecutableSections.size(); ++I) {
3324 InputSection *EX1 = findExidxSection(ExecutableSections[Prev]);
3325 InputSection *EX2 = findExidxSection(ExecutableSections[I]);
3326 if (!isDuplicateArmExidxSec(EX1, EX2)) {
3327 SelectedSections.push_back(ExecutableSections[I]);
3328 Prev = I;
3329 }
3330 }
3331 ExecutableSections = std::move(SelectedSections);
3332 }
3333
3334 size_t Offset = 0;
3335 Size = 0;
3336 for (InputSection *IS : ExecutableSections) {
3337 if (InputSection *D = findExidxSection(IS)) {
3338 D->OutSecOff = Offset;
3339 D->Parent = getParent();
3340 Offset += D->getSize();
3341 } else {
3342 Offset += 8;
3343 }
3344 }
3345 // Size includes Sentinel.
3346 Size = Offset + 8;
3347}
3348
3349InputSection *ARMExidxSyntheticSection::getLinkOrderDep() const {
3350 return ExecutableSections.front();
3351}
3352
3353// To write the .ARM.exidx table from the ExecutableSections we have three cases
3354// 1.) The InputSection has a .ARM.exidx InputSection in its dependent sections.
3355// We write the .ARM.exidx section contents and apply its relocations.
3356// 2.) The InputSection does not have a dependent .ARM.exidx InputSection. We
3357// must write the contents of an EXIDX_CANTUNWIND directly. We use the
3358// start of the InputSection as the purpose of the linker generated
3359// section is to terminate the address range of the previous entry.
3360// 3.) A trailing EXIDX_CANTUNWIND sentinel section is required at the end of
3361// the table to terminate the address range of the final entry.
3362void ARMExidxSyntheticSection::writeTo(uint8_t *Buf) {
3363
3364 const uint8_t CantUnwindData[8] = {0, 0, 0, 0, // PREL31 to target
3365 1, 0, 0, 0}; // EXIDX_CANTUNWIND
3366
3367 uint64_t Offset = 0;
3368 for (InputSection *IS : ExecutableSections) {
3369 assert(IS->getParent() != nullptr);
3370 if (InputSection *D = findExidxSection(IS)) {
3371 memcpy(Buf + Offset, D->data().data(), D->data().size());
3372 D->relocateAlloc(Buf, Buf + D->getSize());
3373 Offset += D->getSize();
3374 } else {
3375 // A Linker generated CANTUNWIND section.
3376 memcpy(Buf + Offset, CantUnwindData, sizeof(CantUnwindData));
3377 uint64_t S = IS->getVA();
3378 uint64_t P = getVA() + Offset;
3379 Target->relocateOne(Buf + Offset, R_ARM_PREL31, S - P);
3380 Offset += 8;
3381 }
3382 }
3383 // Write Sentinel.
3384 memcpy(Buf + Offset, CantUnwindData, sizeof(CantUnwindData));
3385 uint64_t S = Sentinel->getVA(Sentinel->getSize());
3386 uint64_t P = getVA() + Offset;
3387 Target->relocateOne(Buf + Offset, R_ARM_PREL31, S - P);
3388 assert(Size == Offset + 8);
3389}

3393}

3479size_t PPC64LongBranchTargetSection::getSize() const {
3480 return Entries.size() * 8;
3481}
3482
3483void PPC64LongBranchTargetSection::writeTo(uint8_t *Buf) {
3484 // If linking non-pic we have the final addresses of the targets and they get
3485 // written to the table directly. For pic the dynamic linker will allocate
3486 // the section and fill it it.
3487 if (Config->Pic)
3488 return;
3489
3490 for (const Symbol *Sym : Entries) {
3491 assert(Sym->getVA());
3492 // Need calls to branch to the local entry-point since a long-branch
3493 // must be a local-call.
3494 write64(Buf,
3495 Sym->getVA() + getPPC64GlobalEntryToLocalEntryOffset(Sym->StOther));
3496 Buf += 8;
3497 }
3498}
3499
3500bool PPC64LongBranchTargetSection::isNeeded() const {
3501 // `removeUnusedSyntheticSections()` is called before thunk allocation which
3502 // is too early to determine if this section will be empty or not. We need
3503 // Finalized to keep the section alive until after thunk creation. Finalized
3504 // only gets set to true once `finalizeSections()` is called after thunk
3505 // creation. Becuase of this, if we don't create any long-branch thunks we end
3506 // up with an empty .branch_lt section in the binary.
3507 return !Finalized || !Entries.empty();
3508}
3509
3510static uint8_t getAbiVersion() {
3511 // MIPS non-PIC executable gets ABI version 1.
3512 if (Config->EMachine == EM_MIPS) {
3513 // Bump this number everytime we break the ABI to avoid strange runtime
3514 // crashes (happened e.g. when using a binary with the old TLS offset
3515 // on a new kernel).
3516 if (Config->isCheriABI())
3517 return 2; // Bump for every incompatible change
3518 if (!Config->Pic && !Config->Relocatable &&
3519 (Config->EFlags & (EF_MIPS_PIC | EF_MIPS_CPIC)) == EF_MIPS_CPIC)
3520 return 1;
3521 return 0;
3522 }
3523
3524 if (Config->EMachine == EM_AMDGPU) {
3525 uint8_t Ver = ObjectFiles[0]->ABIVersion;
3526 for (InputFile *File : makeArrayRef(ObjectFiles).slice(1))
3527 if (File->ABIVersion != Ver)
3528 error("incompatible ABI version: " + toString(File));
3529 return Ver;
3530 }
3531
3532 return 0;
3533}
3534
3535template <typename ELFT> void elf::writeEhdr(uint8_t *Buf, Partition &Part) {
3536 // For executable segments, the trap instructions are written before writing
3537 // the header. Setting Elf header bytes to zero ensures that any unused bytes
3538 // in header are zero-cleared, instead of having trap instructions.
3539 memset(Buf, 0, sizeof(typename ELFT::Ehdr));
3540 memcpy(Buf, "\177ELF", 4);
3541
3542 auto *EHdr = reinterpret_cast<typename ELFT::Ehdr *>(Buf);
3543 EHdr->e_ident[EI_CLASS] = Config->Is64 ? ELFCLASS64 : ELFCLASS32;
3544 EHdr->e_ident[EI_DATA] = Config->IsLE ? ELFDATA2LSB : ELFDATA2MSB;
3545 EHdr->e_ident[EI_VERSION] = EV_CURRENT;
3546 EHdr->e_ident[EI_OSABI] = Config->OSABI;
3547 EHdr->e_ident[EI_ABIVERSION] = getAbiVersion();
3548 EHdr->e_machine = Config->EMachine;
3549 EHdr->e_version = EV_CURRENT;
3550 EHdr->e_flags = Config->EFlags;
3551 EHdr->e_ehsize = sizeof(typename ELFT::Ehdr);
3552 EHdr->e_phnum = Part.Phdrs.size();
3553 EHdr->e_shentsize = sizeof(typename ELFT::Shdr);
3554
3555 if (!Config->Relocatable) {
3556 EHdr->e_phoff = sizeof(typename ELFT::Ehdr);
3557 EHdr->e_phentsize = sizeof(typename ELFT::Phdr);
3558 }
3559}
3560
3561template <typename ELFT> void elf::writePhdrs(uint8_t *Buf, Partition &Part) {
3562 // Write the program header table.
3563 auto *HBuf = reinterpret_cast<typename ELFT::Phdr *>(Buf);
3564 for (PhdrEntry *P : Part.Phdrs) {
3565 HBuf->p_type = P->p_type;
3566 HBuf->p_flags = P->p_flags;
3567 HBuf->p_offset = P->p_offset;
3568 HBuf->p_vaddr = P->p_vaddr;
3569 HBuf->p_paddr = P->p_paddr;
3570 HBuf->p_filesz = P->p_filesz;
3571 HBuf->p_memsz = P->p_memsz;
3572 HBuf->p_align = P->p_align;
3573 ++HBuf;
3574 }
3575}

3612size_t PartitionIndexSection::getSize() const {
3613 return 12 * (Partitions.size() - 1);
3614}
3615
3616void PartitionIndexSection::finalizeContents() {
3617 for (size_t I = 1; I != Partitions.size(); ++I)
3618 Partitions[I].NameStrTab = Main->DynStrTab->addString(Partitions[I].Name);
3619}
3620
3621void PartitionIndexSection::writeTo(uint8_t *Buf) {
3622 uint64_t VA = getVA();
3623 for (size_t I = 1; I != Partitions.size(); ++I) {
3624 write32(Buf, Main->DynStrTab->getVA() + Partitions[I].NameStrTab - VA);
3625 write32(Buf + 4, Partitions[I].ElfHeader->getVA() - (VA + 4));
3626
3627 SyntheticSection *Next =
3628 I == Partitions.size() - 1 ? In.PartEnd : Partitions[I + 1].ElfHeader;
3629 write32(Buf + 8, Next->getVA() - Partitions[I].ElfHeader->getVA());
3630
3631 VA += 12;
3632 Buf += 12;
3633 }
3634}
